# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1816-united-states-presidential-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The first election for Virginia's 5th congressional district took place on February 2, 1789, for a two-year term to commence on March 4 of that year.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In a race that turned on the candidates' positions on the need for amendments (the Bill of Rights) to the recently ratified U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Constitution, James Madison defeated James Monroe for a place in the House of Representatives of the First Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It is the only congressional election in U.S. history in which two future presidents opposed each other.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They put forward Monroe, a young but experienced politician who was a war hero wounded at the 1776 Battle of Trenton, as a candidate for the seat.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe did not seek the contest, but once drafted campaigned vigorously.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite bitterly cold weather, the two candidates debated outdoors; traveling after one such meeting, Madison suffered frostbite on his face.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although Madison had earlier stated that amendments to the Constitution were not necessary, during the campaign he took the position that they were, but should be proposed by Congress, rather than by an Article V Convention that Anti-Federalists such as Monroe and Henry supported.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison won the election comfortably, to the satisfaction of his supporters such as President-elect George Washington.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The race did not affect Madison's friendship with Monroe, who was elected to the Senate in 1790, and who would serve as Madison's Secretary of State and succeed him as president in 1817.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Madison was born on March 16, 1751 (March 5, 1750, Old Style), at the Belle Grove plantation near Port Conway, Virginia.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He grew up on his parents' estate of Montpelier, and was involved in politics from a young age, serving on the local Committee of Safety at age 23.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He represented Orange County in the Fifth Virginia Convention of 1776.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After service on the Virginia Council of State, where he forged a lifelong friendship with Governor Thomas Jefferson, he was elected to the Second Continental Congress becoming its youngest member.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was one of Virginia's delegates to the Constitutional Convention in 1787, and helped persuade General George Washington to be its chair, which gave the convention the moral authority to propose a new plan of government.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He was the originator of the Virginia Plan that became the basis of the federal government proposed by the convention.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] James Monroe was born April 28, 1758, in Westmoreland County, Virginia, the son of prosperous planters, Spence Monroe and Elizabeth Jones Monroe.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] By 1774, the year he entered the College of William & Mary, both his parents had died.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In early 1776, he joined the Virginia militia and became an officer in the Continental Army, later that year being severely wounded at the Battle of Trenton.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He left Continental service in 1779, and was made a colonel in the state militia.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the war, Monroe studied law under Jefferson and was elected to the House of Delegates in 1782, and to the Congress of the Confederation in New York in 1783, where he sought to expand the powers of that body.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1784, Madison was told by Jefferson that Monroe wanted to begin a correspondence with him, beginning a relationship that would last until Monroe's death in 1831.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men differed over whether their state should ratify the Constitution at the Virginia Ratifying Convention, with Madison in favor and Monroe against.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Opponents deemed the proposed national government to be too powerful, and many wanted a second constitutional convention in order to place limits on it.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite their efforts, Virginia narrowly ratified the Constitution on June 25, 1788.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe, like Jefferson, believed that there needed to be a Bill of Rights protecting fundamental liberties from infringement by the new federal government.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Ratification had not been a major issue in the Virginia legislative elections of 1788, since it was expected to be decided by the Ratifying Convention that had just been chosen by the voters.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] When the General Assembly convened in October 1788, though, it had a majority of Anti-Federalist members, and was led by Henry, a member of the House of Delegates for Prince Edward County.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry sought to avenge the Anti-Federalist defeat at the Ratifying Convention, and also believed Madison would not seek amendments, or would do so in a lukewarm fashion.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On October 31, the General Assembly re-elected Madison to his seat in the lame-duck Confederation Congress, a body that would cease to exist with the coming of the new federal government.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's motives in allowing this are uncertain, with some historians stating it was to keep Madison in New York, far from the elections for Congress taking place in Virginia.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Historian Chris DeRose hypothesizes that Madison's seat there was his if he wanted it, and his acceptance meant that he expected to remain in New York (where the new Congress would convene) and win his seat in Virginia without needing to campaign.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison, who sought election to the House of Representatives, yielded to Washington and the Federalist minority in the legislature and allowed his name to be put forward in the legislature's election for Virginia's two U.S. senators—until 1913, senators were elected by the state legislatures.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry nominated two Anti-Federalists, Richard Henry Lee and William Grayson, while Madison was the sole Federalist named.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry told the General Assembly that Madison was "unworthy of the confidence of the people" and that his election "would terminate in producing rivulets of blood throughout the land".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry's nominees were elected, Lee with 98 votes and Grayson with 86, while the defeated Madison gained 77.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly turned its attention to dividing the state into congressional districts.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's home county, Orange, was placed in a district with seven others, five of which had elected representatives to the Ratifying Convention who had opposed ratification, while Orange and one other had voted in favor and one county's delegation had split its vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The General Assembly required that candidates live in the district, a qualification not found in the federal Constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Fauquier County, closely associated with Orange both geographically and economically, had supported ratification, but was excluded despite the efforts of Federalists.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Despite some stating that Henry had contrived a district in which Madison was sure to be defeated, Thomas Rogers Hunter in a journal article examined the question, and concluded, "the district was compact and bounded on all sides by natural geographic features.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Simply put, Patrick Henry did not attempt to gerrymander James Madison out of a seat in the first U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Congress." Virginia's 5th congressional district consisted of the counties of Albemarle, Amherst, Culpeper, Fluvanna, Goochland, Louisa, Orange and Spotsylvania.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Some of these counties were later divided, so the district that Madison contested also included the present-day counties of Greene, Madison, Nelson and Rappahannock.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] French Strother, a long-time Virginia legislator from Culpeper County who had opposed ratification at the Virginia Convention, was solicited as a candidate to oppose Madison, but declined.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] William Cabell, of Amherst County, was also considered as an Anti-Federalist candidate but Monroe was selected instead.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Both Strother and Cabell threw their support behind Monroe.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A resident of Spotsylvania County, Monroe was reluctant to run against his friend Madison, but was probably encouraged by Henry, George Mason and other Anti-Federalists, though discouraged by his uncle, Joseph Jones.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] His service in the Revolutionary War, and his political service after it, were electoral assets.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The selection of Monroe was enough to worry Washington: "Sorry indeed should I be if Mr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Federalist Henry Lee wrote to him, "I profess myself pleased with your exclusion from the senate & I wish it may so happen in the lower house [in which case] you will be left qualified to take part in the administration, which is the place proper for you".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, Henry Lee believed Madison would win, calling Monroe "the beau".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison disliked electioneering, but realized he would have to campaign hard to win the race.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Fifth District race would be the only congressional election in history to oppose two future U.S. presidents.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The largest issue in the campaign was the question of a Bill of Rights protecting personal freedoms as amendments to the Constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's view had been that these were unnecessary as the Federal government had only limited power and that in any event, the new government should be allowed to operate for a time before changes were made to the Constitution.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To take such a stance in the campaign would be political suicide, and Madison recognized that there was widespread support for such amendments.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] But he felt it to be important that Congress proposed them, believing that route to be a quicker, easier, and safer means of passage than an Article V convention, which was favored by the Anti-Federalists such as Monroe.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Nevertheless, he was skeptical about the effect of such amendments, calling them "parchment barriers", ineffective if the Federal government was determined to bypass them.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He told the voters that if elected, he would work diligently for the passage of a Bill of Rights.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's earlier stances made it easy to depict him in this light.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge to support a Bill of Rights if elected left the question of direct taxation as the major difference between them.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe believed the power of the Federal government to directly tax the citizens to be not only unnecessary, but injurious to American liberty.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He felt the government could raise money by tariffs, by the sale of public lands, or by borrowing.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison responded that were the Federal government unable to tax citizens directly, tariffs would be the major source of revenue, and this would disproportionately hurt the South, which had few manufactures and imported heavily from overseas.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He also stated that having federal taxes paid in each state would help bind the nation together as giving each a financial stake in the Union's success.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been in New York, helping to wrap up the affairs of the old Congress of the Confederation.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He received letters from other parts of Virginia from those who believed the residency requirement unconstitutional, offering to have him run there, but he preferred to run in his home district, and he declined.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] A trip to Virginia on horseback or in a carriage would be personally hard on Madison, then suffering from a bad case of hemorrhoids.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On December 8, 1788, he wrote to Jefferson (who was in Paris) that he would return to Virginia to campaign for his election, a decision prompted in part by warnings from Virginians that he could not win without personally fighting for the seat.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He arrived at Washington's plantation, Mount Vernon, on December 18, for a visit that lasted until he returned home to Orange County and his estate, Montpelier, just after Christmas.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] From the time Madison arrived in Virginia, the weather was unusually cold and snowy; the candidates often had to speak in freezing conditions, and the last weekend before the election saw 10 inches (250 mm) of snow.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Aware he was not an orator of Henry's quality, Madison launched a letter-writing campaign, advocating for the new Constitution; though initially taken by surprise, Monroe also set out his positions in letters.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It was Madison's intent, in writing to key citizens in each community, both to enlist support, and have the recipients circulate the letters locally or publish them in local newspapers.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] For Monroe's part, according to DeRose, he "poured himself into the campaign with frenetic energy, determined to campaign everywhere, to personally engage voters, and to make liberal use of his pen to correspond with community leaders.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Considering him as being able to render his Country Great Services on this important occasion".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On January 7, 1789, Virginians chose electors who would vote for the first U.S. president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The districts for this were not coextensive with congressional districts, since Virginia was entitled to 12 electors but only 10 congressmen.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Still, six of the counties in the Fifth District were in the same district for choosing an elector, and the race featured a Federalist and Anti-Federalist, though both were pledged to vote for Washington for president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Goochland and Louisa counties were not in that electoral district, but Buckingham County was.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Federalist, Edward Stevens, was elected, and outpolled his opponent within the Fifth District, but both parties took hope from the result, with the Anti-Federalists cheered by the fact that Stevens had easily taken Spotsylvania County, where the local favorite Monroe would presumably do better.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates sought to appeal to the local religious communities, of which the Baptists were the most influential.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] That community had taken the position that the Constitution did not provide sufficient protection for their religious liberty.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison's pledge of support for amendments defused much of the Anti-Federalist anger against him.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The two men were quite friendly with each other, and decided to travel together between debates, riding from courthouse to courthouse, making speeches before large crowds.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] These debates showed the physical contrast between the tall, athletic Monroe, who had a full head of brown hair, and the short, slender Madison and his receding hairline.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They often rode together, ate together, and lodged in the same room.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 18th century Virginia, Court Day, a different day in each local county, was not only an opportunity for lawyers and judges to try cases, but a social gathering, including fairs, markets, and other events.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The candidates addressed those present, sometimes speaking for hours to the largest crowds they were likely to find during the campaign.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Henry Lee wrote to Washington three days later, "Mr Madison is gaining ground fast but still he is involved in much doubt & difficulty.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The debate that DeRose deemed perhaps the most significant of the race took place one evening at the Hebron Lutheran Church in Culpeper (today in Madison County).
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Lutherans, like the Baptists, had been persecuted in America, and generally voted as a bloc to maximize their influence.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe and Madison attended the worship service, after which there was musical entertainment featuring fiddles.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They and the congregation then went outside, and the two candidates debated on the front porch as the congregation stood in the bitter cold, with snow on the ground, likely for hours.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Riding away afterwards, likely home to Montpelier, Madison suffered a frostbitten nose.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In his old age, former president Madison would tell the story of that night, and point to the left side of his nose, saying he had battle scars.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] White males who were 21 years of age or older and who owned 50 acres (20 ha) of unimproved land or half that with a house were eligible to vote in the Fifth District.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Approximately 5,189 voters formed the district's electorate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Per the 1790 census, there were 11,231 free white males age over 16 in the district, so about half of free white men were able to vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The total population (including women, slaves and children) of the district was 91,007, so the electorate made up less than 6% of the total population, and perhaps 12–15% of those aged over 21.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] There was no secret ballot in Virginia elections in 1789; voters entered the local courthouse and publicly declared their votes, to be recorded by a clerk.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The elections were administered by county sheriffs, normally the senior justice of the peace who had not already served in that capacity.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Due to the bitterly cold weather in the Fifth District, the sheriffs in some counties extended voting beyond February 2, allowing more voters to reach their county courthouse.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] This was not authorized by Virginia law, but had also occurred in the voting for presidential electors the previous month.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] To get out the vote, Madison's supporters sent wagons around to transport voters to the polls.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] They brought one very old man from a distance, and he listened to them talk and asked if the Monroe spoken of was the son of Spence Monroe, formerly of Westmoreland County.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On being told he was, the man declared he would vote for James Monroe, for "I do not know James Madison", but Spence Monroe had once fed him, clothed him and sheltered him.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Once the polls closed, the local sheriff went to the door of the courthouse and proclaimed the result.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] It took time for complete results to be compiled; partial returns were printed in newspapers.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] On February 10, the sheriffs of the eight counties of the Fifth District met at Albemarle's courthouse, as the county first named in the election statute, to certify the results.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Their returns indicated that Madison won the election with 1,308 votes to 972 for Monroe.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In Madison's home county of Orange, he received 216 votes to Monroe's 9, in Culpeper 256 to Monroe's 103; he won Albemarle County by 69 votes and Louisa by 104.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had given considerable attention to Orange, apparently spending the day of the polls there despite the urgings of some supporters to base himself for the day in a more populous county, and two-thirds of his margin of victory came from Orange.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Strong Baptist support for Madison there contributed to the outcome.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Madison had been able to hold down the margin in strongly Anti-Federalist Amherst to 246–145 for Monroe, who also took his home county of Spotsylvania by 74 votes, Fluvanna by 21 and Goochland by 1 vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The Baptists favored Madison due to his record of support for religious liberty.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] After the election, Madison wrote to Jefferson, "It was my misfortune to be thrown into a contest with our friend, Col.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] The occasion produced considerable efforts among our respective friends.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] According to Stewart, "Barely thirty years old, Monroe had time to make his way.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In the House of Representatives, Madison introduced and guided to passage the amendments that became known as the Bill of Rights.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He broke with Washington over the administration's policies, and allied with Jefferson, helping gain the latter's election to the presidency, and became his Secretary of State in 1801.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He succeeded Jefferson as president in 1809.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Although defeated for Congress, Monroe's frequent court appearances as a lawyer kept him in the public eye in Virginia.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] In 1790, after Grayson's death, the General Assembly elected him to the U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] He served thereafter in a number of offices, including, twice, Governor of Virginia, and in 1811 Madison named Monroe as Secretary of State.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1789-virginia-s-5th-congressional-district-election] Monroe was elected president in succession to Madison in 1816, taking office the following year.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The **1790–91 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections occurred during the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1790 and 1791, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the nine senators in Class 1.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 25, 1790 elections in Rhode Island.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Except if/when noted, the number following candidates is the whole number vote(s), not a percentage.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated before March 4, 1791; ordered by election date.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winners were seated March 4, 1791; ordered by state.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of these elections involved the Class 1 seats.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winners were seated after March 4, 1791, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] All of the senators from Connecticut were Pro-Administration through 1795.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Oliver Ellsworth was re-elected in 1791.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Samuel Johnson resigned March 3, 1791, at the end of the 1st Congress and Roger Sherman was elected June 13, 1791, to finish the term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Charles Carroll won re-election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 20.00%, or 15 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Senator, Tristam Dalton sought re-election but was eliminated before the third ballot.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The third ballot saw the election of George Cabot, who had been a member of the Massachusetts Provincial Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The election in New York was held January 19, 1791, by the New York State Legislature.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent Philip Schuyler's term would expire March 3, 1791.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At the State election in April 1790, nominal Federalist majorities were elected to both houses of the 14th New York State Legislature, but many Federalists were friendly to the Democratic-Republican Governor George Clinton, party lines not being drawn very strictly then.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The incumbent Philip Schuyler ran for re-election as the candidate of the Federalist Party.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] New York State Attorney General Aaron Burr was the candidate of the Democratic-Republican Party, but was at that time a rather moderate politician, opposing the ultras of both parties.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Burr was the choice of both the State Senate and the State Assembly, and was declared elected.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Schuyler was defeated despite the nominal majority of his party.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Many of the Federalists took the opportunity to show their disapproval of both Schuyler's haughtiness and the financial policies of Alexander Hamilton, the U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Secretary of the Treasury and Schuyler's son-in-law.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Besides, the Livingston faction of the Federalist Party felt betrayed after the election of Rufus King over their candidate James Duane in 1789, and now allied themselves with Clinton and later became Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Obs.: Burr had a majority of 5 votes in the Assembly, but the exact number of votes is unclear.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] In 1791, the legislature failed to elect due to a disagreement on procedure.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The seat would remain vacant until 1793.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Moses Robinson were elected by the Vermont House of Representatives and Governor and Council in January 1791, anticipating Vermont's admission to the union.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Vermont was admitted as the 14th state on March 4, 1791.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The Senate had adjourned on March 3, at the completion of the 1st United States Congress; the 2nd United States Congress held a one-day session on March 4, and was not scheduled to convene again until October 24.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] As a result of this congressional schedule Bradley and Robinson had not been seated when the Vermont House of Representatives convened in early October, 1791.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] At this legislative session, some members suggested that the January election of Bradley and Robinson had been premature, since Vermont had not yet been admitted to the union.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley and Robinson volunteered to resign the credentials of their January elections; on October 17, the Governor and Council voted again, and selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] The House of Representatives then voted a second time, and also selected Bradley and Robinson.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Bradley was selected for the "short term" (Class 3), which expired on March 3, 1795.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Robinson received the "long term" (Class 1), which expired on March 3, 1797.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] William Grayson died March 12, 1790, and John Walker was appointed to continue the term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Future President James Monroe was elected in November 1790 to finish the term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1790-and-1791-united-states-senate-elections] Monroe was re-elected in 1791 to the next term, as well.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The **1792–93 United States Senate elections** were held on various dates in various states, coinciding with President George Washington's unanimous re-election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senate elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1792 and 1793, and a seat may have been filled months late or remained vacant due to legislative deadlock.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, terms were up for the ten senators in Class 2.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Formal organized political parties had yet to form in the United States, but two political factions were present: The coalition of Senators who supported George Washington's administration were known as the Pro-Administration Party, and the Senators against him as the Anti-Administration Party.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Virginia's elections are considered a single race here.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] After the June 1792 admission of Kentucky.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Two Pro-Administration senators (Benjamin Hawkins of North Carolina and John Langdon of New Hampshire) changed to Anti-Administration.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The vacant seat in Pennsylvania was filled February 28, 1793 by an Anti-Administration senator.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these elections, the winner was seated before March 4, 1793; ordered by election date.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In these regular elections, the winner was seated on March 4, 1793; ordered by state.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] All of the elections involved the Class 2 seats.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] In this special election, the winner was seated after March 4, 1793, the beginning of the next Congress.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] One-term Anti-Federalist William Few was defeated by fellow Anti-Federalist, James Jackson.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson won 24 votes in the Georgia House of Representatives and 11 in the State Senate for a combined total of 35.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Few won 3 in the House and 2 in the Senate for a combined total of 5.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Jackson took office as a member of the 3rd United States Congress on March 4, 1793.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] He would later resign in 1795 to run for his state's legislature.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent John Brown, who had previously been elected in a special election was easily reelected with no opposition and 100% of votes from the legislators.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Richard Potts won election to fill the seat vacated by Charles Carroll over Josh Hoskins Stone by a margin of 21.84%, or 19 votes, for the Class 1 seat.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Senator Paine Wingate was not reelected.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The New Hampshire General Court instead elected Federalist Samuel Livermore, a U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Livermore, like his fellow senator, John Langdon, would go on to serve as President Pro-Tempore during this term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Pro-Administration Samuel Johnston lost re-election to Anti-Administration Alexander Martin for the class 2 seat.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The other senator, Benjamin Hawkins, switched his support from Pro- to Anti-Administration.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] There was a special election on February 28, 1793, for the Class 1 seat from Pennsylvania.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Incumbent William Maclay's term had ended on March 3, 1791, but the legislature failed to elect a successor due to a disagreement on the procedure to be followed in the election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] The seat remained vacant until Albert Gallatin was elected by the Pennsylvania General Assembly to the seat during this election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Upon agreement between the two houses of the Pennsylvania General Assembly, the House of Representatives and the Senate, regarding the procedure to elect a new Senator, an election was finally held on February 28, 1793.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] On February 28, 1794, the Senate determined that Gallatin did not satisfy the citizenship requirement for service and he was removed from office.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Gallatin was replaced in the Senate by a special election in 1794.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-Administration senator Richard Henry Lee resigned October 8, 1792, just before the March 3, 1793 end of term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-and-1793-united-states-senate-elections] Anti-administration John Taylor of Caroline was elected October 18, 1792 to finish Lee's term and then re-elected in 1793 to the next term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 3, 1800.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election in U.S. history to be a rematch, the first election where an incumbent president lost re-election, leading to the first time in modern history where a national government changed hands peaceably following a free election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams had narrowly defeated Jefferson in the 1796 election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the rules of the electoral system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As Jefferson received the second-most votes in 1796, he was elected vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1800, unlike in 1796, both parties formally nominated tickets.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Jefferson and Aaron Burr, while the Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of Adams and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each party formed a plan by which one of their respective electors would vote for a third candidate or abstain so that its preferred presidential candidate (Adams for the Federalists and Jefferson for the Democratic-Republicans) would win one more vote than the party's other nominee.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The chief political issues revolved around the fallout from the French Revolution and the Quasi-War.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists favored a strong central government and close relations with Great Britain.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans favored decentralization to the state governments, and the party attacked the taxes the Federalists imposed.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans also denounced the Alien and Sedition Acts, which the Federalists had passed to make it harder for immigrants to become citizens and to restrict statements critical of the federal government.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans were well organized at the state and local levels, while the Federalists were disorganized and suffered a bitter split between their two major leaders, Adams and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to historian John Ferling, the jockeying for electoral votes, regional divisions, and the propaganda smear campaigns created by both parties made the election recognizably modern.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] At the end of a long and bitter campaign, Jefferson and Burr each won 73 electoral votes, Adams won 65, and Pinckney won 64.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept New England, the Democratic-Republicans dominated the South, and the parties split the Mid-Atlantic states of New York, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans' assumption that one or more electors in Rhode Island, Vermont, New Jersey, Georgia, Kentucky, or Tennessee would vote for Jefferson and not Burr resulted in a tie, known as the Burr dilemma.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It necessitated a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the terms laid out in the Constitution, the outgoing House of Representatives chose between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Burr was accused of campaigning for the presidency himself in the contingent election despite being a member of Jefferson's party.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation cast one vote, and a victory in the contingent election required one candidate to win a majority of the state delegations.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots of the contingent election, as most Federalist representatives backed Burr and all Democratic-Republican representatives backed Jefferson.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton favored Jefferson over Burr, and he convinced several Federalists to switch their support to Jefferson, giving Jefferson a victory on the 36th ballot.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson became the second consecutive incumbent vice president to be elected president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1824 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties used congressional nominating caucuses to formally nominate tickets for the first time.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of incumbent President John Adams of Massachusetts and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney had fought in the American Revolutionary War and later served as the minister to France.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Vice President Thomas Jefferson of Virginia and former Senator Aaron Burr of New York.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had been the runner-up in the previous election and had co-founded the party with James Madison and others, while Burr was popular in the electorally important state of New York.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] While the 1800 election was a re-match of the 1796 election, it ushered in a new type of American politics, a two-party republic and acrimonious campaigning behind the scenes and through the press.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On top of this, the election pitted the "larger than life" Adams and Jefferson, who were formerly close allies turned political enemies.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was bitter and characterized by slander and personal attacks on both sides.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists spread rumors that the Democratic-Republicans were radical atheists who would ruin the country (based on the Democratic-Republican support for the French Revolution).
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1798, George Washington had complained "that you could as soon scrub the blackamoor white, as to change the principles of a professed Democrat; and that he will leave nothing unattempted to overturn the Government of this Country".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, the Democratic-Republicans accused Federalists of subverting republican principles with the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They also accused Federalists of favoring Britain in its war with France in order to promote aristocratic, anti-democratic values.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was attacked by both the opposition Democratic-Republicans and a group of so-called "High Federalists" aligned with Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] "High Federalists" considered Adams too moderate and would have preferred the leadership of Alexander Hamilton instead.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton had apparently grown impatient with Adams and wanted a new president who was more receptive to his goals.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] During Washington's presidency, Hamilton had been able to influence the federal response to the Whiskey Rebellion (which threatened the government's power to tax citizens).
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When Washington announced that he would not seek a third term, the Federalists and Adams regarded himself as next-in-line.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton appears to have hoped in 1796 that his influence within an Adams administration would be as great as or greater than in Washington's.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] By 1800, Hamilton had come to realize that Adams was too independent and thought the Federalist vice presidential candidate, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, more suited to serving Hamilton's interests.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In his third sabotage attempt toward Adams, Hamilton quietly schemed to elect Pinckney to the presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Given Pinckney's lack of political experience, he would have been expected to be open to Hamilton's influence.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Hamilton's plan backfired and hurt the Federalist party, particularly after one of his letters, a scathing criticism of Adams that was fifty-four pages long, fell into the hands of a Democratic-Republican and soon after became public.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It embarrassed Adams and damaged Hamilton's efforts on behalf of Pinckney, not to mention speeding Hamilton's own political decline.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The contemporarily unorthodox public campaigning methods employed in 1800 were first employed by Jefferson's running mate and campaign manager, Aaron Burr, who is credited by some historians with inventing the modern electioneering process.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Yet, throughout this entire process, the candidates themselves were conspicuously missing from the campaigning, at least publicly, due to fears that they may otherwise be tagged as "demagogues".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Even a visit John Adams made to Washington was made into a public point of contention.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Partisans on both sides sought any advantage they could find.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In several states, this included changing the process of selecting electors to ensure the desired result.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, Democratic-Republican legislators replaced the popular vote with selection by the state legislature.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, the Democratic-Republican-controlled legislature switched from electoral districts to a general ticket, a winner-take-all system.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist legislators also switched methods, switching from districts and general tickets to legislature votes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, respectively.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, the General Assembly was split, with the Democratic-Republican-dominated House wishing to retain the general ticket and the Federalist-controlled Senate wishing to return to the district system, hoping to win at least some electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, this deadlock was broken by a last-minute compromise between the chambers that gave the Democratic-Republican eight electors and the Federalists seven.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the rejection to change the selection method backfired on the Federalists.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1800, two months before the assembly elections, the Democratic-Republicans attempted to pass a bill that would switch from a legislature vote to electoral districts, hoping they would secure at least a third of the state's seats.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists defeated the measure, believing that they would win control of both chambers and award all of the state's electoral votes to the Federalist nominees.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the April state elections, Aaron Burr's effective mobilization of the vote in New York City led to a reversal of the Federalist majority in the state legislature, providing crucial support for the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In response to the Federalist defeat, Hamilton attempted to get Governor John Jay to call a special session of the outgoing Federalist-dominated New York legislature.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's plan was for the outgoing assembly to pass legislation that would establish the popular election of electors through electoral districts, a strategy almost certain to secure nine or ten of the twelve elector slots for the Federalists.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jay refused to participate in such an underhanded scheme.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist legislature in Connecticut did not change the method of voting but instead passed a "stand up" election law, mandating that all votes be cast publicly and orally, an intimidating procedure that ordinarily favored those in power.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As election day neared, the election was too close to call.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The last state to vote, South Carolina, chose its electors on December 2, and would become key to determining the election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The state elections in mid-October had produced an assembly that was about evenly divided between committed Federalists and Republicans, with 16 unaffiliated representatives who were all strongly pro-Jefferson.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the elected Jeffersonians were also supporters of Pinckney, the revered native son of the state.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] If South Carolina's electors gave their votes to Jefferson and Pinckney, then Pinckney would place an electoral vote behind Jefferson, becoming the vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Pinckney stayed loyal to the instructions of his party's caucus and was adamant that any elector who voted for him must also vote for Adams.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With uncommitted legislators not willing to desert Jefferson and Pinckney unwilling to abandon Adams, the uncommitted legislators eventually reluctantly agreed to support Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the United States Constitution as it then stood, each elector cast two votes, and the candidate with a majority of the votes was elected president, with the vice presidency going to the runner-up.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists therefore arranged for one of their Rhode Island electors to vote for John Jay instead of Charles Pinckney to prevent the election from resulting in a tie.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] A letter to Jefferson from Peter Freneau assured him that a member of the Republican delegation from South Carolina would vote for George Clinton instead of Aaron Burr and a report from Georgia indicated that two of its electors would deny Burr their votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, this information proved faulty.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, all of the Democratic-Republican electors cast their votes for both Jefferson and Burr, 73 in all for each of them.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to a provision of the United States Constitution, a tie in a case of this type had to be resolved by the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the outgoing House, the Federalists had a majority of 60 seats to 46.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When the electoral ballots were opened and counted on February 11, 1801, the certificate of election from Georgia was different than the others.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia had sent the original oral ballot.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 2004, David Fontana and Bruce Ackerman asserted that Georgia's certificate did not take the constitutionally mandated form of a "List of all the Persons voted for, and of the Number of Votes for each".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They claimed that Vice President Jefferson, who was presiding over the counting of electoral votes in his role as President of the Senate, immediately counted the votes from Georgia as votes for Jefferson and Burr, though they observed that "no objections were raised".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney, and John Jay) in the House of Representatives.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With these votes, the total number of votes for Jefferson and Burr was 73, which gave them a majority of the total, but they were tied.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Holly Brewer, a legal historian, argued that the counting of the Georgia ballot did not support Ackerman and Fontana's theory.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Brewer's arguments helped to influence Vice President Pence's decision to reject the theory that he had such powers, via Judge J.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson and Burr carried every state that had supported the Democratic-Republicans in 1796, made gains in Maryland, and picked up Burr's home state of New York.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the six states choosing electors by some form of popular vote, they won a landslide over Adams and Pinckney, polling 15,846 more votes than the Federalist ticket.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams made gains in Pennsylvania and North Carolina, but these votes were not enough to offset the Democratic-Republican gains elsewhere.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 155 counties and independent cities making returns, Jefferson and Burr won in 115 (74.19%), whereas the Adams ticket carried 40 (25.81%).
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time that Vermont voted for the Federalists and the last time a Federalist won electoral votes from Pennsylvania.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of two elections contested between people who would at some point serve as vice president, the other being 1968.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 16 states that took part in the 1800 election, six (Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Tennessee, and Virginia) used some kind of popular vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island and Virginia, voters elected their state's entire Electoral College delegation at large; Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee all used some variation of single-member districts.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the rest, electors were chosen by the state legislature.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Not until the 1836 presidential election would all states have direct popular selection of electors (except South Carolina, which had its state legislature vote for electors until 1868).
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Popular vote records for several states are incomplete, and the returns from Kentucky and Tennessee appear to have been lost; states did not print or issue electoral ballots, and most were issued by newspapers that supported a particular party or candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Newspapers are also the main source of voting records in the early 19th century, and frontier states such as Tennessee had few in operation, without any known surviving examples.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee chose each of their electors from specially-drawn single-member districts, the results from which are as follows.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In February 1801, the members of the House of Representatives balloted as states to determine whether Jefferson or Burr would become president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] There were sixteen states, each with one vote; an absolute majority of nine was required for victory.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It was the outgoing House of Representatives, controlled by the Federalist Party, that was charged with electing the new president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was the great enemy of the Federalists, and a faction of Federalist representatives tried to block him and elect Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalists voted for Burr, giving Burr six of the eight states controlled by Federalists.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The seven delegations controlled by Democratic-Republicans all voted for Jefferson, and Georgia's sole Federalist representative also voted for him, giving him eight states.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Vermont delegation was evenly split and cast a blank ballot.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining state, Maryland, had five Federalist representatives to three Democratic-Republicans; one of its Federalist representatives voted for Jefferson, forcing that state delegation also to cast a blank ballot.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Publicly, Burr remained quiet between mid-December 1800 and mid-February 1801, when the electoral votes were counted.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Behind the scenes, he faced mounting pressure from within the party to step aside if he and Jefferson should tie in electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Regardless, he refused to disavow the presidency, writing in December 1800 to Representative Samuel Smith (R-MD) that he would not "engage to resign" if chosen president, adding that the question was "unnecessary, unreasonable and impertinent".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Rumors circulated that Representative James A.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard (F-DE) had—purportedly in Burr's name—approached Smith and Edward Livingston (R-NY) with offers of political appointments if they voted for Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither came to pass, however, chiefly due to Hamilton's energetic opposition to Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton embarked on a frenzied letter-writing campaign to get Federalist Representatives to support Jefferson because he was "by far not so dangerous a man" as Burr; in short, he would much rather have someone with wrong principles than someone devoid of any.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] From February 11 to 17, the House cast a total of 35 ballots; each time eight state delegations voted for Jefferson, one short of the necessary majority of nine.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On February 17, on the 36th ballot, Bayard changed his vote from Burr to no selection, joined by his allies in Maryland and Vermont.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This changed the Maryland and Vermont votes from no selection to Jefferson, giving him the votes of 10 states and the presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The four representatives present from South Carolina, all Federalists, also changed their 3–1 selection of Burr to four abstentions.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Due to the experiences of this and the previous election, sentiment for a new way of selecting the president and vice president rose significantly, resulting in the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the 2015 musical *Hamilton* by Lin Manuel Miranda, the contest between Jefferson and Burr is recounted in "The Election of 1800".
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The song focuses on Alexander Hamilton's role in deciding the outcome of the 1801 contingent election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The musical simplifies the complicated multiple elections somewhat, portraying Adams's unpopularity as making the real choice between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Historians wrote that Adams did not lose that badly in the original election, with the musical inflating the size of Jefferson's victory.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It implies Hamilton's support for Jefferson over Burr was the catalyst for the Burr–Hamilton duel; in fact, while that helped sour relations between Burr and Hamilton, the duel was ultimately provoked by Hamilton's statements about Burr in the 1804 New York gubernatorial election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1816.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican ticket of secretary of state James Monroe and the governor of New York Daniel D.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Tompkins defeated the de facto Federalist candidate, the senior U.S. senator from New York Rufus King.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Although not formally nominated, King became the last Federalist presidential candidate upon receiving 34 votes from Federalist unpledged electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In the subsequent election, the Federalists carried three states but did not field their own candidate, instead supporting the incumbent Monroe, before disappearing by the end of the 1820s.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The outgoing president James Madison did not seek re-election to a third consecutive term.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe emerged as the Democratic-Republican frontrunner and secured the party's nomination at its congressional nominating caucus in March, narrowly defeating the secretary of war William H.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus nominated Tompkins for vice president over the governor of Pennsylvania Simon Snyder.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists were disorganized following the end of the War of 1812 and did not hold a caucus or formally select a candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] King himself remained aloof from the campaign and did nothing to promote his candidacy.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] No consensus on a vice presidential candidate emerged among the Federalist electors, who scattered their votes between four candidates.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe benefited from the popularity of the outgoing Madison administration and resurgent nationalism following the end of the war.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Madison's 1816 message to Congress endorsed an ambitious economic program that robbed the Federalists of much of their platform, most notably chartering the Second Bank of the United States.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In spite of significant discontent with the caucus system and the incumbent Virginia dynasty, the Democratic-Republicans were able to avoid a major factional schism in contrast to the previous election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists meanwhile were demoralized, dogged by accusations of treason, and ill-prepared to mount a national campaign.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Most took Monroe's election for granted and did not attempt to prevent it.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In three states where electors were chosen by the legislature, Federalists controlled the selection process and appointed unpledged electors who voted for King.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe carried the 16 remaining states, including every state where electors were chosen by popular vote, amidst widespread voter apathy and anemic turnout.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe followed an uncertain path to the nomination in 1816.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] He had feuded with Madison for most of the preceding three decades, running against him for a seat in the United States House of Representatives in 1789 and for the presidency in 1808.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe mended relations with Madison during the War of 1812, serving as secretary of state and secretary of war in the latter's administration, and by 1816 was positioning himself as the president's natural successor.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe was not personally popular, and his candidacy encountered resistance from northern Democratic-Republicans and others opposed to the extension of the Virginia dynasty.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] During the winter of 1815–16, New York governor Daniel D.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Tompkins and Monroe's successor as secretary of war William H.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford emerged as rivals for the presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Popular in his home state, Tompkins could count on the loyal support of the Anti-Clintonian faction of the New York Democratic-Republican Party, but his candidacy struggled to attract a national following.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] While the New York General Assembly formally nominated him for president on February 14, his lack of name recognition, youth, and volatility were seen as serious disadvantages.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] By March, Tompkins had seemingly given up all hope of his nomination and instead focused his efforts on the vice presidency.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Although Crawford publicly denied interest in the presidency, his candidacy quickly gathered significant support from editors and politicians ahead of the party's congressional nominating caucus, and by February had amassed enough strength to present a serious challenge to Monroe.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Despite this, Crawford remained hesitant to openly seek the nomination.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Having personally assured the secretary of state that he would not be a candidate in 1816, he was reluctant to damage his standing in the party with a fight for the nomination.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The continued enthusiasm for his candidacy following his public refusal in February left the war secretary unsure of how to proceed.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Substantial public opinion opposed the caucus system as corrupt, undemocratic, and potentially unconstitutional.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] While Monroe preferred to retain the caucus system, Crawford's popularity among Democratic-Republicans in Congress made calling a caucus immediately disadvantageous to Monroe's chances of gaining the nomination.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] When finally an anonymous notice announced the date of the caucus as March 12, the meeting was attended by only 58 members, principally supporters of Crawford.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The gathering was judged too small to command public credibility, and on the motion of Jeremiah Morrow of Ohio, the caucus adjourned until March 16.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] During the recess, Crawford instructed the U.S. senators from Georgia Charles Tait and William W.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Bibb to withdraw his candidacy, having decided to postpone his ambitions until 1824.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] When the caucus met again on the 16th, all but 22 Democratic-Republican members were in attendance.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor again moved that it was "inexpedient" to nominate a presidential candidate, but were voted down; the caucus then nominated Monroe by a vote of 65 to 54.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe owed his majority over Crawford to the 11 Virginians in attendance, who supplied the margin of victory.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford received the votes of the New York, New Jersey, Georgia, and Kentucky delegations, notwithstanding their candidate's withdrawal.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 22 Democratic-Republican members who did not attend the caucus, the majority were Crawfordites who absented themselves at Crawford's request to allow Monroe's nomination.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In the event of his defeat, Crawford had instructed Tait and Bibb to issue a statement that he had been drafted without his consent; this the senators neglected to do.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Crawford would subsequently attribute Monroe's lack of support for his candidacy in 1824 to this embarrassment.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Maneuvering for the vice presidency began in the weeks preceding the caucus, when the identity of the presidential candidate was still an open question.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Sensing his presidential chances lagging, Tompkins advertised his willingness to accept the vice presidency under either Monroe or Crawford.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Several others were considered available candidates, including the governor of Pennsylvania Simon Snyder and the speaker of the U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives Henry Clay of Kentucky.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Snyder's hopes were dashed when he failed to secure the formal endorsement of the Pennsylvania congressional delegation.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] It was widely assumed that Crawford and Tompkins each sought to recruit the other for the second place on the ticket.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The New York delegation floated a Tompkins–Crawford ticket that could unite all foes of the Virginia dynasty; when this failed, they approached Clay, to no avail.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Tompkins emerged as the overwhelming favorite when the caucus met on March 16 and was nominated by a large majority, while Snyder finished a distant second.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Passed over for the presidency, the New Yorker substantially exceeded Monroe's margin over Crawford, winning the votes of nearly three quarters of the members in attendance.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party entered the election in disarray.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Following peace with Britain in 1815, "the strength that the Federalists had shown in the middle states during the war years melted away." Disconnected state parties lacked a unifying national organization capable of fielding candidates or mounting a national campaign.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Where Federalists were more than a negligible presence, charges of disloyalty hounded the party in the wake of the Hartford Convention.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] If the Federalists were to choose a candidate, King appeared by far the likeliest possibility.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] A respected senator and former delegate to the Constitutional Convention who had twice been the party's vice presidential candidate in 1804 and 1808, by 1816 King was the only individual capable of uniting the party's remaining supporters.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In February, the *New York Evening Post* predicted that King and the former Speaker of the U.S.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] House of Representatives Langdon Cheves would be the nominees of the Federalist caucus for president and vice president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the interim, the New York Federalist Party nominated King for governor in the April 1816 election after the party's original candidate, William W.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] King lost the election to Tompkins, and although the Democratic-Republican majority was not overwhelming, the defeat ended any hope of King's nomination for president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] While some Federalists suggested the former U.S. senator from Maryland John Eager Howard or even Crawford as possible candidates, no serious movement to nominate either man ever materialized.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists thus entered the fall campaign without a ticket, and with most party leaders resigned to an inevitable Democratic-Republican victory.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The failure of the Federalist Party to nominate a ticket effectively conceded the election to Monroe.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In New Jersey, Ohio, Rhode Island, Vermont, and in every state south of the Potomac River, the Federalists did not seriously contest the election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist unpledged electors ran in several states, and in Pennsylvania, Monroe's opponents fielded an Independent ticket supported by disaffected Democratic-Republicans and Federalists.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Lacking a candidate, the opposition all but ignored the presidential race and instead reserved their energies for state and local elections in which the remnants of regional Federalist strength might still be salvaged.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In New York and New Hampshire, where a real effort was made to defeat the Democratic-Republican ticket, the Federalist campaign was distracted and uncoordinated.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] So great was the sense of inevitability surrounding Monroe's election that most public speculation focused on the composition of his incoming cabinet.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Rufus King shared the view of nearly all observers who considered Monroe's election a foregone conclusion.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] He took no part in the campaign and said or did nothing to indicate that he considered himself a candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Following his gubernatorial defeat, King encouraged his colleagues to accept Monroe's election and suggested the Federalist Party should disband.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Nothing in King's private correspondence suggests his candidacy for president; in a letter to Christopher Gore dated November 5, he referred to Monroe as running unopposed.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The partisan press did not consider King a candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican *Vermont Gazette* laughed that Connecticut's Federalist electors "probably do not know for whom they shall vote themselves!" As late as December 3, the Federalist *Boston Daily Advertiser* admitted it did not know for whom the state's Federalist electors would vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] King would not learn of his selection by 34 Federalist electors until after the electoral colleges had already met.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus system was a major issue in the campaign.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] A gathering of members of Congress had selected the Democratic-Republican national ticket in every consecutive election since 1796.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral candidates and candidates for state office were commonly chosen by similar gatherings of state legislators.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] By design, the caucus system gave elected lawmakers substantial influence over the choice of party nominees for state and national office.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] This feature attracted criticism from Federalists and anti-caucus Democratic-Republicans who argued that the practice of caucus nominations undermined democratic elections, gave undue influence to career officeholders, and potentially violated the constitutional separation of powers.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] With no organized opposition to Monroe, they noted that the election effectively had been decided by members of Congress and alleged that the constitutional election process had been subverted.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] The perception that the caucus had forced its choice upon the nation irrespective of the opinions of most voters was particularly salient.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] "A president is to be made thinks I," went one editorial, "but what shall we call the process?
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Not an election! for the people have nothing to do with it and the electors have nothing to do with it.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] One half of the republicans and all the federalists are against the man; but the caucus have said 'it shall be so,' and it must be so." The Federalist press made a significant effort to capitalize on opposition to the caucus.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Opposition to the Virginia dynasty was a significant theme in the contest for the Democratic-Republican nomination that carried over into the general election.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Three of the four previous presidents had been Virginians; the only president from New England, John Adams, served a single term from 1797 to 1801.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In the aftermath of the caucus, the Federalist press attempted to keep the issue alive.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In June, the *Charlestown Courier* reprinted an anonymous pamphlet, the *Exposition of the Motives for Opposing the Nomination of Mr.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe for the Office of President of the United States,* purportedly the work of the "fifty-four Democrats" who had voted to nominate Crawford in the caucus.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Probably written by John Armstrong Jr., the piece alleged that party leaders had ruthlessly blocked the advancement of Monroe's rivals in order to continue the line of Virginian presidents, irrespective of Monroe's evident unfitness for office.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Several Federalist editors suggested adopting Crawford as the party's candidate for president, but party leaders ultimately failed to agree upon this strategy.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Monroe won the election decisively, carrying 33 of the 39 constituencies representing 183 electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] He received a majority of the electoral votes from 16 states, including every state where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Three states where electors were chosen by the legislature—Connecticut, Delaware, and Massachusetts—and three popular election districts in Maryland chose unpledged Federalist electors, representing 38 electoral votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Four Federalist electors (the three Maryland Federalists and one elector from Delaware) did not vote; the remaining 34 voted for Rufus King.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] There was no agreement among the Federalists as to a vice presidential candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Tompkins received the votes of all 183 Democratic-Republican electors.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Indiana entered the Union as the nineteenth state on December 11, 1816.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] When Congress met to count the electoral votes on February 22, 1817, John W.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Taylor, the member from New York's 11th congressional district, objected to counting Indiana's electoral votes on the grounds that it had not been a state at the time of the meeting of the electoral colleges.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Opinion in the House was overwhelmingly in favor of counting Indiana's votes.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Ingham, the question of the legality of Indiana's votes was postponed indefinitely, and the final electoral count was read with Indiana's votes included.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Nineteenth century election laws required voters to vote directly for members of the Electoral College rather than for president.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] This sometimes resulted in small differences in the number of votes cast for electors pledged to the same presidential candidate if some voters did not vote for all the electors nominated by a party, or if one or several electors ran on multiple tickets.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table compares the results for the most popular elector pledged to each ticket.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] For the single-member electoral districts in Maryland, all votes for electors pledged to one party or nominee are counted in cases where multiple electors were pledged to the same presidential candidate.
[src:1816-united-states-presidential-election/1816-united-states-presidential-election] Returns from Tennessee and one Kentucky district appear to have been lost.
